      <description>&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;hr&gt;Xianzu_Monk_Tunare wrote:&lt;br &gt; I don't know.  I think it's better to wing the people off of the armor progression quests about at 20 or so because that's about the time in which they can actually start getting their own upgrades  as well as gain money reasonably fast enough to start buying or making better armor.  Having these quests go all the way to lvl 50 would be more harmful than helpful.  People would start getting to 50 and hit a brick wall when it comes to how to upgrade their character.  Post 50 the upgrades are more sensitive to how well you preform than they are from 20-50.  I'd rather have 20 or 30 levels to spend actually learning how to best to choose what is a good upgrade when making bad choices isn't going to be nearly as costly as it will no be if you don't have to start learning until you're over lvl 50 when many armor upgrades cost more than most level 50-60 players can make in a week while playing normally.&lt;hr&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;I much prefer being given quests to do rather than having to go to the bazaar. They could make them all require groups to complete the quests. They could be equivalent to or even slightly less/more than the cultural quest armors are for those levels, maybe even different stats, like focusing more on WIS for shamans. Many of the trade skill armors are fillers, not really meant for using as a complete set, especially if you want to focus on a certain stat. This give more alternate paths to getting armors. The point about grouping, learning how to upgrade your character, and costs can still be found. I didn't use every piece I got from the 10-20 armor quests.&lt;br&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;hr&gt;The main thing I have against the task window is that eliminates completely the need to solve anything.  The task quests are simply presolved quests with ingame walk throughs.  There is nothing at all to figure out.  Tasks are tasks not quests.  In case someone doesn't understand what I mean, tasks are a list of things that someone told you what exactly to do and you go do them.  But a quest is something that you get asked to go do, but you have to figure out some of what needs to be done yourself, yes you're told some things directly but other things you have to think out yourself or solve a riddle or make a jump of faith based on a subtle hint in the text.  The best quests have always been the ones which the community had to help each other to solve each step.  So unless they include something that requires players to figure something particular out at a variety of steps anything moved or added to the task system will not be a quest but a task. &lt;hr&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;They don't necessarily have to go into the details they do for many of the armor tasks and the money tasks. They could merely just record the quest text you get while doing/getting the quest. If your suggesting a different method and window, sure, id go for that too. I don't want hand holding in doing the quests, I just want a record of the quests. Would also great to be able to look up past tests i've completed.</description>
